    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 26th with a clear emphasis on exploiting the soft matchup against Spencer Arrighetti. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (79.92) is our strongest play of the day; the combination of a favorable park, a 19% boost from the opposing pitcher\u2019s skill, and his elite SB potential against a slow-delivery pitcher makes him our primary anchor. **James Wood** (73.17) also surges into elite territory as a leadoff hitter against a shaky arm in a favorable matchup, while **Mickey Moniak** (71.89) and **Corbin Carroll** (71.54) round out our high-efficiency OF core. **Mickey Moniak** in particular benefits from a massive 14% boost due to platoon advantages and the top-of-the-order usage, though he carries a slight risk due to an unfavorable wind forecast. **Josh Naylor** (69.13) provides stability at 1B, capitalizing on the SP matchup to secure a strong daily efficiency score.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was leaving **Trevor Story** (55.08) out of the starting lineup. Despite a favorable park factor, he was squeezed out by the sheer volume of high-scoring, high-upside plays against Arrighetti and the optimizer's strict adherence to our SB-weighted scoring. **Jose Caballero** (56.31) narrowly retains his starting spot despite a lower base projection than **Trevor Story**, purely because his stolen base upside is prioritized to maintain our competitive edge in the scarcest category. We are tracking \"Lineup Pending\" statuses closely, particularly for **Luis Campusano** and **Dalton Rushing**; any late-afternoon shifts in their batting orders could force a pivot to the bench, as **Luis Campusano** is currently operating near our efficiency floor. Overall, we are positioned to capitalize on high-volume production, provided our starters avoid weather-induced volatility and the late-lineup risks associated with **Max Muncy** and **Tyler Soderstrom**.",
